   247→    <div class="header">
   248→        <div class="header-content">
   249→            <h1>Chebyshev Circles</h1>
   250→            <nav class="nav">
   251→                <a href="./blueprint/">Blueprint</a>
   252→                <a href="./docs/">API Docs</a>
   253→                <a href="./graph/">Dependency Graph</a>
   254→                <a href="https://github.com/e-vergo/ChebyshevCircles">GitHub</a>
   255→            </nav>
   256→        </div>
   257→    </div>
   258→
   259→    <div class="container">
   260→        <div class="content">
   261→            <h2>Rotated Roots of Unity and Chebyshev Polynomials</h2>
   262→
   263→            <div class="badges">
   264→                <a href="https://github.com/e-vergo/ChebyshevCircles/actions/workflows/lean_action_ci.yml">
   265→                    <img src="https://github.com/e-vergo/ChebyshevCircles/actions/workflows/lean_action_ci.yml/badge.svg" alt="CI">
   266→                </a>
   267→                <a href="https://e-vergo.github.io/ChebyshevCircles/">
   268→                    <img src="https://img.shields.io/badge/docs-passing-brightgreen" alt="Documentation">
   269→                </a>
   270→                <a href="LICENSE">
   271→                    <img src="https://img.shields.io/badge/license-Apache%202.0-blue.svg" alt="License">
   272→                </a>
   273→            </div>
   274→
   275→            <p>
   276→                When the N-th roots of unity are rotated by angle φ and projected onto the real axis and then taken to be
   277→                the roots of a polynomial, after scaling by 2<sup>N-1</sup> the polynomial formed from these projections
   278→                equals the N-th Chebyshev polynomial of the first kind plus a φ-dependent constant.
   279→            </p>
   280→
   281→            <div class="theorem-box">
   282→                <h3>Main Theorem</h3>
   283→                <div class="theorem-statement">
   284→theorem rotated_roots_yield_chebyshev (N : ℕ) (φ : ℝ) (hN : 0 < N) :<br>
   285→&nbsp;&nbsp;∃ (c : ℝ), scaledPolynomial N φ = Polynomial.Chebyshev.T ℝ N + C c
   286→                </div>
   287→                <div class="construction">
   288→                    <strong>Construction:</strong>
   289→                    <ul>
   290→                        <li>Projected roots: <code>cos(φ + 2πk/N)</code> for k = 0, ..., N-1</li>
   291→                        <li>Unscaled polynomial: <code>P(x) = ∏(x - cos(φ + 2πk/N))</code></li>
   292→                        <li>Scaled polynomial: <code>S(x) = 2<sup>N-1</sup> · P(x)</code></li>
   293→                        <li>Result: <code>S(x) = T<sub>N</sub>(x) + c(φ)</code></li>
   294→                    </ul>
   295→                </div>
   296→            </div>
   297→
   298→            <div class="visualization">
   299→                <figure>
   300→                    <img src="chebyshev_gifs/chebyshev_animation_N5.gif" alt="N=5 Chebyshev Circle Animation">
   301→                    <figcaption>
   302→                        Animation showing N=5 roots of unity being rotated. The regular pentagon (coral edges) rotates with
   303→                        the roots (red points). Vertical projection lines show how roots project to the real axis (pink points),
   304→                        which serve as roots for the blue polynomial curve. The displayed polynomial equation updates in real-time,
   305→                        showing that the curve's shape remains a 5th-degree Chebyshev polynomial (T₅(x)) while only the constant
   306→                        term <em>c</em> changes with rotation angle φ.
   307→                    </figcaption>
   308→                </figure>
   309→            </div>
   310→
   311→            <h2>Project Components</h2>
   312→
   313→            <div class="components">
   314→                <div class="component-card">
   315→                    <h3>Formal Verification</h3>
   316→                    <p>Complete Lean 4 formalization across 10 modules with full proofs.</p>
   317→                    <div class="stats">
   318→                        <div class="stat">
   319→                            <div class="stat-number">3,457</div>
   320→                            <div class="stat-label">Lines of Proof</div>
   321→                        </div>
   322→                        <div class="stat">
   323→                            <div class="stat-number">0</div>
   324→                            <div class="stat-label">Sorry Statements</div>
   325→                        </div>
   326→                    </div>
   327→                    <a href="./docs/">View API Documentation →</a>
   328→                </div>
   329→
   330→                <div class="component-card">
   331→                    <h3>Blueprint</h3>
   332→                    <p>Interactive documentation showing dependency structure and formalization status.</p>
   333→                    <p>Navigate through the proof architecture and see cross-references between mathematical exposition and Lean code.</p>
   334→                    <a href="./blueprint/">Explore Blueprint →</a>
   335→                </div>
   336→
   337→                <div class="component-card">
   338→                    <h3>Dependency Graph</h3>
   339→                    <p>Visual representation of how all lemmas, theorems, and definitions connect.</p>
   340→                    <p>See the complete proof structure from foundational results to the main theorem.</p>
   341→                    <a href="./graph/">View Dependency Graph →</a>
   342→                </div>
   343→
   344→                <div class="component-card">
   345→                    <h3>Research Paper</h3>
   346→                    <p>Publication-ready mathematics paper (14 pages) with complete proofs in classical notation.</p>
   347→                    <p>Traditional exposition targeting a general mathematical audience at graduate level.</p>
   348→                    <a href="https://github.com/e-vergo/ChebyshevCircles/tree/main/paper">Read Paper →</a>
   349→                </div>
   350→            </div>
   351→
   352→            <h2>Why This Connection Matters</h2>
   353→
   354→            <p>
   355→                This theorem reveals a surprising geometric interpretation of Chebyshev polynomials. Rather than defining
   356→                them via recurrence relations or cosine composition, we can construct them by taking N equally-spaced points
   357→                on the unit circle, rotating them by any angle, projecting onto the real axis, building the polynomial with
   358→                these projections as roots, and scaling by 2<sup>N-1</sup>. The result is always T<sub>N</sub>(x) plus a constant.
   359→            </p>
   360→
   361→            <p>
   362→                This provides a bridge between discrete geometry (roots of unity on the circle), harmonic analysis
   363→                (discrete orthogonality relations), and polynomial theory (Chebyshev polynomials).
   364→            </p>
   365→
   366→            <h3>Proof Strategy</h3>
   367→
   368→            <p>
   369→                The verification establishes that rotated roots and Chebyshev roots have identical power sums (except the
   370→                zeroth), which by Newton's identities implies they generate polynomials differing only by a constant term.
   371→                The power sum equality relies on discrete orthogonality of complex exponentials over N-th roots of unity,
   372→                the discrete analog of continuous Fourier orthogonality.
   373→            </p>
   374→
   375→            <h2>Getting Started</h2>
   376→
   377→            <p>
   378→                <strong>Prerequisites:</strong> Lean 4 (v4.25.0-rc2), basic familiarity with polynomials, complex numbers,
   379→                and trigonometric identities.
   380→            </p>
   381→
   382→            <p>
   383→                Clone the repository and build the project:
   384→            </p>
   385→
   386→            <div class="theorem-statement">
   387→git clone https://github.com/e-vergo/ChebyshevCircles.git<br>
   388→cd ChebyshevCircles<br>
   389→lake exe cache get<br>
   390→lake build
   391→            </div>
   392→
   393→            <p>
   394→                Explore the <a href="./blueprint/">Blueprint</a> for an interactive map of the formalization,
   395→                check the <a href="./docs/">API Documentation</a> for detailed proofs, or view the
   396→                <a href="./graph/">Dependency Graph</a> to understand the proof structure.
   397→            </p>
   398→        </div>
   399→    </div>
   400→</body>
